{"cursor":"23140","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Social influence' occurs when one's emotions, opinions, or behaviors are\naffected by others. http://qualities-of-a-leader.com/personal-mbti-type-\nanalysis/ Social influence takes many forms and can be seen in conformity,\nsocialization, peer pressure, obedience, leadership, persuasion, sales, and\nmarketing. In 1958, Harvard psychologist, Herbert Kelman identified three broad\nvarieties of social influence. Kelman, H. (1958). Compliance,\nidentification, and internalization: Three processes of attitude change. Journal\nof Conflict Resolution, 1, 51-60.\n\n#'[[Compliance (psychology)|Compliance]]' is when people appear to agree with\n#others, but actually keep their dissenting opinions private. '[[Identification\n#(psychodynamic)|Identification]]' is when people are influenced by someone who\n#is liked and respected, such as a famous celebrity. '[[Internalization]]' is\n#when people accept a belief or behavior and agree both publicly and privately.\n\nMorton Deutsch and Harold Gerard described two psychological needs that lead\nhumans to conform to the expectations of others. These include our need to be\nright (informational social influence), and our need to be liked (normative\nsocial influence). Deutsch, M. & Gerard, H. B. (1955). A study\nof normative and informational social influences upon individual judgment.\nJournal of Abnormal and Social Psychology, 51, 629-636. Informational\ninfluence (or social proof) is an influence to accept information from another\nas evidence about reality. Informational influence comes into play when people\nare uncertain, either because stimuli are intrinsically ambiguous or because\nthere is social disagreement. Normative influence is an influence to conform to\nthe positive expectations of others. In terms of Kelman's typology, normative\ninfluence leads to public compliance, whereas informational influence leads to\nprivate acceptance.\n","linknr":358,"url":"Social_influence","recorded":1364194470,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Social_influence&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Social_influence&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-head","#p-search","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Conformity","/wiki/Socialization","/wiki/Peer_pressure","/wiki/Obedience_(human_behavior)","/wiki/Leadership","/wiki/Persuasion","/wiki/Sales","/wiki/Marketing","/wiki/Herbert_Kelman","#cite_note-Kelman-2","/wiki/Compliance_(psychology)","/wiki/Identification_(psychodynamic)","/wiki/Internalization","/wiki/Need","/wiki/Informational_social_influence","/wiki/Normative_social_influence","#cite_note-Gerard-3","#Types","#Kelman.27s_varieties","#Compliance","#Identification","#Internalization","#Conformity","#Minority_influence","#Self-fulfilling_prophecy","#Reactance","#Obedience","#Persuasion","#Antecedents","#Social_impact_theory","#Cialdini.27s_.22Weapons_of_Influence.22","#Unanimity","#Status","#Culture","#Emotions","#Musicological_Influence","#Social_structure","#Social_networks","#See_also","#References","#Further_reading","#External_links","/w/index.php?title=Social_influence&action=edit&section=1","/wiki/Social_psychology","/w/index.php?title=Social_influence&action=edit&section=2","/wiki/A